commentary: Mohammed Shami to Guptill, no run huge lbw appeal as Guptill shoulders arms. India don't go for the review saying it was too high, signalling to a spot on his thigh. Insane batting from the opener. Even if the good length ball hadn't nipped back in, that is way too close to the off stump. Guptill lifts the bat high over his head. Then looks straight at the umpire deciding his fate. Shaun George says no. Ooooh, that was close!

commentary: Mohammed Shami to Guptill, OUT plays on!. Reward for ridiculously good line and length. And honestly, it almost seems as if Guptill hasn't been picking Shami out the hand. Hasn't been comfortable with the way the ball is coming out. This one hits a length on and around off stump and wobbles back into the right-hander, he's too slow with his forward defensive and it piggy-backs off an inside edge and crashes into the stumps. Hundredth ODI wicket for Shami - the fastest by an Indian in ODIs

commentary: Mohammed Shami to Munro, OUT through him! It's his first ball from round the wicket and it's enough! Delicious bowling. And all this havoc is because of seam movement. And that too only about an inch or two. Shami usually presents the seam so beautifully. It comes down bolt upright as he hits a fuller length, outside off, drawing the left-hander to drive away from his body. That's because Munro's feet aren't quite covering for that deadly bit of movement and when that happens, you have to be circumspect with your shots. Munro isn't, and he pays for it

commentary: Chahal to Taylor, OUT he's claiming a caught and bowled! And replays show he's right. Exceptional bowling. This is the result of the other trick in his bag - change of pace. And it's almost like he's sensed his moment. Taylor's been itching to smash Chahal. But the legspinner's been too good with his drift and dip. Now the batsman has to make a choice. Take a risk. He comes dancing out of his crease. Chahal is ready for it. Pulls his length back. Draws his pace down. Doesn't let Taylor anywhere near the ball and the shot - a tame push down the pitch - results in a low catch, which he takes diving forward. Insaaaaaaanely good.

commentary: Chahal to Latham, OUT return catch has been sent upstairs with soft signal out. This is a full ball the Latham doesn't get to the pitch of. Wants to drive to long-on, but he chips it to Chahal's left. It dips on the legspinner as he takes that. He isn't moving forward, per se, just sort of falling to his left...but third umpire is convinced he's got fingers under this. Didn't take too long for that decision. One look from the extra cover angle, one from front on, and Nigel Llong has seen enough evidence to go with the soft signal. Chahal does it again with his loop. And backs it up with his catching. Brilliant spell

commentary: Kuldeep Yadav to Ferguson, no run huge lbw appeal but umpire George rules it not out and India have no reviews. This looks so close though. A tossed up googly that Ferguson can't read. He's lunging forward, playing for the one that turns into him, and is comfortably beaten on the outside edge. From there on, he's struck on the back pad in line with off stump. Is there too much spin there? Would it miss? Nope, replay shows three reds

commentary: Ferguson to Kohli, OUT caught behind! The Ferguson short ball works. And that's largely because it climbs up to his badge. Kohli's the kind to take on the short ball. If only to show bowlers they won't have their way. He's got out this way before, especially when his body's the target and sometimes even when the bouncer is straying down leg - as this is. Goes for the hook and gets a thin tickle through to the keeper.

commentary: Ferguson to Rayudu, FOUR runs between keeper and slip! Taylor is wide, at second slip, if he'd been at orthodox first slip, that would have been a dolly. This is Rayudu not fancying Ferguson's pace. His feet aren't moving. Goes searching for a good length ball outside off and offers a thick edge that should really have been gobbled up. Latham tries his best, diving to his right, but he is never getting there
